It seems wc is counting `\r` and `\n` as a character and you&#39;re not. 

Add to that the BOM you are ignoring and it gives the difference you are seeing. 

You should probably not be reading by line if you want to count the `\r` and the `\n`. If that&#39;s the case, I would read by character, and then keep a state every time you read a `\r` to ignore the following `\n` to increment the number of lines. Actually, it seems you are making several passes, one for the lines, another for the characters, and I guess another for the words.

So you just need this:

```java
public static long countChars(File inputFile) {
    long count = 0;

    try (Reader reader = new FileReader(inputFile)) {
        while (reader.read() &gt; 0) count ++;
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }

    return count;
}
```

But you could solve it in one pass with the suggestion I made about the state for saying the last read was a `\r` for not counting the following `\n`.

&gt; _&quot;... Why are there two line breaks per line rather than per one? Surely every line has a line break at the end of it? ...&quot;_

There is a full article on _Wikipedia_ regarding this exact situation.\
_[Wikipedia &amp;ndash; Newline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newline)_.

&gt; _&quot;... What is the extra single character? ...&quot;_

That, I&#39;m unsure of.&amp;nbsp; Possibly an extra new-line delimiter, or even a _null_.\
Or, maybe the result of some type of encoding and decoding process.

&gt; _&quot;... Is it naive to simply double the line count and add it onto the character count (and then +1)? Will this trip me up in some edge case somehow? ...&quot;_

I wouldn&#39;t.&amp;nbsp;  It&#39;s a lot simpler to just re-evaluate.

For reference, here is an example of how I would count the, _&quot;... number of lines, bytes, words and characters&quot;_.

```java
BufferedReader r = null;
try {
    r = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(&quot;files/pg132.txt&quot;));
    Pattern p = Pattern.compile(&quot;[\\w&#39;-]+&quot;);
    Matcher m;
    String s;
    int c, lines, words, chars, cr, lf;
    lines = words = chars = cr = lf = 0;
    while ((c = r.read()) != -1) {
        chars++;
        switch (c) {
            case &#39;\r&#39; -&gt; cr++;
            case &#39;\n&#39; -&gt; lf++;
        }
    }
    r.close();
    r = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(&quot;files/pg132.txt&quot;));
    while ((s = r.readLine()) != null) {
        lines++;
        m = p.matcher(s);
        while (m.find()) words++;
    }
    out.printf(&quot;%,7d lines%n&quot;, lines);
    out.printf(&quot;%,7d words%n&quot;, words);
    out.printf(&quot;%,7d chars%n&quot;, chars);
    out.printf(&quot;%,7d cr%n&quot;, cr);
    out.printf(&quot;%,7d lf%n&quot;, lf);
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
} finally {
