`ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` means there is something wrong with how you are updating your variables.  
you have to try reverse an array using recursion:  
```
public class Main {
   static int beginning = 0;
   static int end;

   public static void main(String[] args) {
       int[] myArray = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
       end = myArray.length - 1;
       Problem5(myArray);
       for (int num : myArray) {
           System.out.print(num + &quot; &quot;);
       }
   }

   public static void Problem5(int[] myArray) {
       if (beginning &gt;= end) {
           return;
       } else {
           int temp = myArray[beginning];
           myArray[beginning] = myArray[end];
           myArray[end] = temp;
       }
       beginning++;
       end--;
       Problem5(myArray);
   }
}

```
Before the elements and in the if statement i cheked `beginning &gt;= end` in order to avoid the variable error.

In the solution below you can reverse the array without any extra space, no extra array, and no temp for swapping the start and end of the array.

```Java
    public int[] Problem5(int[] arr) {
        return reverse(arr, 0, arr.length - 1); // use length - 1 to avoid index out of bound in accessing array
    }

    // By this method you can pass the new start and end 
    // Also you will do the recursion by this method
    private static int[] reverse(int[] arr, int start, int end) {
        if (start &gt; end) {
            return arr;
        }

        // swap integers without temp
        // x, y = 2, 3
        // x = x + y = 2 + 3 = 5
        // y = x - y = 5 - 3 = 2
        // x = x - y = 5 - 2 = 3
        arr[start] = arr[start] + arr[end];
        arr[end] = arr[start] - arr[end];
        arr[start] = arr[start] - arr[end];

        //Move the indexes
        start++;
        end--;

        return reverse(arr, start, end);
    }
```

