That was a challenge, and I had to look it up.

Utilize the _[Arrays#copyOfRange](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Arrays.html#copyOfRange(T[],int,int))_ method to _shallow copy_ the array.

```java
&lt;T&gt; void reverse(T[] a) {
    if (a.length == 1) 
        return;
    T t = a[0];
    a[0] = a[a.length - 1];
    a[a.length - 1] = t;
    reverse(Arrays.copyOfRange(a, 1, a.length));
}
```

Alternately, here is an example using a starting and ending index.

```java
&lt;T&gt; void reverse(T[] a, int i, int j) {
    if (i == j) 
        return;
    T t = a[i];
    a[i] = a[j];
    a[j] = t;
    reverse(a, ++i, --j);
}
```

With an instance variable, a solution can be like this:

```
public class Test {

    private int currentIndex = 0; // It probably needs a better name

    public int[] Problem5(int[] myArray) {
        if (currentIndex == myArray.length / 2) {
            // You have reached the middle of the array.
            // Everything is swapped
            currentIndex = 0; // Reset index if you need to use the same instance again
            return myArray;
        }
        int firstIndex = currentIndex;
        int secondIndex = myArray.length - 1 - firstIndex;

        int temp = myArray[firstIndex];
        myArray[firstIndex] = myArray[secondIndex];
        myArray[secondIndex] = temp;
        currentIndex++; // Update the index before the next recursive call
        return Problem5(myArray);
    }
